# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oauth2-flows-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] In computer systems, an **access token** contains the security credentials for a login session and identifies the user, the user's groups, the user's privileges, and, in some cases, a particular application.*"RFC 6749 - The OAuth 2.0 Authorization Framework".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] *RFC Editor*.* In some instances, one may be asked to enter an access token (e.g.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] 40 random characters) rather than the usual password (it therefore should be kept secret just like a password).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] An *access token* is an object encapsulating the security identity of a process or thread.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] A token is used to make security decisions and to store tamper-proof information about some system entity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] While a token is generally used to represent only security information, it is capable of holding additional free-form data that can be attached while the token is being created.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Tokens can be duplicated without special privilege, for example to create a new token with lower levels of access rights to restrict the access of a launched application.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] An access token is used by Windows when a process or thread tries to interact with objects that have security descriptors (*securable objects*).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] In Windows, an access token is represented by the system object of type `Token`.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] An access token is generated by the logon service when a user logs on to the system and the credentials provided by the user are authenticated against the authentication database.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] The authentication database contains credential information required to construct the initial token for the logon session, including its user id, primary group id, all other groups it is part of, and other information.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] The token is attached to the initial process created in the user session and inherited by subsequent processes created by the initial process.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Whenever such a process opens a handle to any resource which has access control enabled, Windows reconciles the data in the target object's security descriptor with the contents of the current effective access token.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] The result of this access check evaluation is an indication of whether any access is allowed and, if so, what operations (read, write/modify, etc.) the calling application is allowed to perform.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Primary tokens can only be associated to processes, and they represent a process's security subject.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Processes initially inherit a copy of the parent process's primary token.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Impersonation is a security concept implemented in Windows NT that allows a server application to temporarily "be" the client in terms of access to secure objects.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] , same as impersonation but extended to remote systems to which the server connects (through the preservation of credentials).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] The client can choose the maximum impersonation level (if any) available to the server as a connection parameter.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/access-token] Impersonation tokens are usually created and associated to the current thread implicitly, by IPC mechanisms such as DCE RPC, DDE and named pipes.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Authentication is relevant to multiple fields.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In art, antiques, and anthropology, a common problem is verifying that a given artifact was produced by a certain person, or in a certain place (i.e. to assert that it is not counterfeit), or in a given period of history (e.g. by determining the age via carbon dating).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In computer science, verifying a user's identity is often required to allow access to confidential data or systems.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] It might involve validating personal identity documents.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The *first* type of authentication is accepting proof of identity given by a credible person who has first-hand evidence that the identity is genuine.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] When authentication is required for art or physical objects, this proof could be a friend, family member, or colleague attesting to the item's provenance, perhaps by having witnessed the item in its creator's possession.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] With autographed sports memorabilia, this could involve someone attesting that they witnessed the object being signed.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A vendor selling branded items implies authenticity, while they may not have evidence that every step in the supply chain was authenticated.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The *second* type of authentication is comparing the attributes of the object itself to what is known about objects of that origin.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] For example, an art expert might look for similarities in the style of painting, check the location and form of a signature, or compare the object to an old photograph.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] An archaeologist, on the other hand, might use carbon dating to verify the age of an artifact, do a chemical and spectroscopic analysis of the materials used, or compare the style of construction or decoration to other artifacts of similar origin.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The physics of sound and light, and comparison with a known physical environment, can be used to examine the authenticity of audio recordings, photographs, or videos.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Documents can be verified as being created on ink or paper readily available at the time of the item's implied creation.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Attribute comparison may be vulnerable to forgery.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In general, it relies on the facts that creating a forgery indistinguishable from a genuine artifact requires expert knowledge, that mistakes are easily made, and that the amount of effort required to do so is considerably greater than the amount of profit that can be gained from the forgery.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In art and antiques, certificates are of great importance for authenticating an object of interest and value.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Certificates can, however, also be forged, and the authentication of these poses a problem.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] For instance, the son of Han van Meegeren, the well-known art-forger, forged the work of his father and provided a certificate for its provenance as well.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Criminal and civil penalties for fraud, forgery, and counterfeiting can reduce the incentive for falsification, depending on the risk of getting caught.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Currency and other financial instruments commonly use this second type of authentication method.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Bills, coins, and cheques incorporate hard-to-duplicate physical features, such as fine printing or engraving, distinctive feel, watermarks, and holographic imagery, which are easy for trained receivers to verify.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The *third* type of authentication relies on documentation or other external affirmations.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In criminal courts, the rules of evidence often require establishing the chain of custody of evidence presented.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] This can be accomplished through a written evidence log, or by testimony from the police detectives and forensics staff that handled it.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Some antiques are accompanied by certificates attesting to their authenticity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Signed sports memorabilia is usually accompanied by a certificate of authenticity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] These external records have their own problems of forgery and perjury and are also vulnerable to being separated from the artifact and lost.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Consumer goods such as pharmaceuticals, perfume, and clothing can use all forms of authentication to prevent counterfeit goods from taking advantage of a popular brand's reputation.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] As mentioned above, having an item for sale in a reputable store implicitly attests to it being genuine, the first type of authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The second type of authentication might involve comparing the quality and craftsmanship of an item, such as an expensive handbag, to genuine articles.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The third type of authentication could be the presence of a trademark on the item, which is a legally protected marking, or any other identifying feature which aids consumers in the identification of genuine brand-name goods.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] With software, companies have taken great steps to protect from counterfeiters, including adding holograms, security rings, security threads and color shifting ink.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Counterfeit products are often offered to consumers as being authentic.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Counterfeit consumer goods, such as electronics, music, apparel, and counterfeit medications, have been sold as being legitimate.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Efforts to control the supply chain and educate consumers help ensure that authentic products are sold and used.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Even security printing on packages, labels, and nameplates, however, is subject to counterfeiting.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Products or their packaging can include a variable QR Code.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A QR Code alone is easy to verify but offers a weak level of authentication as it offers no protection against counterfeits unless scan data is analyzed at the system level to detect anomalies.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] To increase the security level, the QR Code can be combined with a digital watermark or copy detection pattern that are robust to copy attempts and can be authenticated with a smartphone.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A secure key storage device can be used for authentication in consumer electronics, network authentication, license management, supply chain management, etc.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Generally, the device to be authenticated needs some sort of wireless or wired digital connection to either a host system or a network.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Nonetheless, the component being authenticated need not be electronic in nature as an authentication chip can be mechanically attached and read through a connector to the host e.g. an authenticated ink tank for use with a printer.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] For products and services that these secure coprocessors can be applied to, they can offer a solution that can be much more difficult to counterfeit than most other options while at the same time being more easily verified.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Packaging and labeling can be engineered to help reduce the risks of counterfeit consumer goods or the theft and resale of products.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Some package constructions are more difficult to copy and some have pilfer indicating seals.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Counterfeit goods, unauthorized sales (diversion), material substitution and tampering can all be reduced with these anti-counterfeiting technologies.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Packages may include authentication seals and use security printing to help indicate that the package and contents are not counterfeit; these too are subject to counterfeiting.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Packages also can include anti-theft devices, such as dye-packs, RFID tags, or electronic article surveillance tags that can be activated or detected by devices at exit points and require specialized tools to deactivate.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In literacy, authentication is a readers’ process of questioning the veracity of an aspect of literature and then verifying those questions via research.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The fundamental question for authentication of literature is – Does one believe it?
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Related to that, an authentication project is therefore a reading and writing activity in which students document the relevant research process.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The documentation materials for literature go beyond narrative texts and likely include informational texts, primary sources, and multimedia.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The process typically involves both internet and hands-on library research.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] When authenticating historical fiction in particular, readers consider the extent that the major historical events, as well as the culture portrayed (e.g., the language, clothing, food, gender roles), are believable for the period.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Literary forgery can involve imitating the style of a famous author.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] If an original manuscript, typewritten text, or recording is available, then the medium itself (or its packaging – anything from a box to e-mail headers) can help prove or disprove the authenticity of the document.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] However, text, audio, and video can be copied into new media, possibly leaving only the informational content itself to use in authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Various systems have been invented to allow authors to provide a means for readers to reliably authenticate that a given message originated from or was relayed by them.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The opposite problem is the detection of plagiarism, where information from a different author is passed off as a person's own work.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A common technique for proving plagiarism is the discovery of another copy of the same or very similar text, which has different attribution.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In some cases, excessively high quality or a style mismatch may raise suspicion of plagiarism.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The process of authentication is distinct from that of authorization.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Whereas authentication is the process of verifying that "you are who you say you are", authorization is the process of verifying that "you are permitted to do what you are trying to do".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] While authorization often happens immediately after authentication (e.g., when logging into a computer system), this does not mean authorization presupposes authentication: an anonymous agent could be authorized to a limited action set.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Similarly, the establishment of the authorization can occur long before the authorization decision occurs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A user can be given access to secure systems based on user credentials that imply authenticity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A network administrator can give a user a password, or provide the user with a key card or other access devices to allow system access.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In this case, authenticity is implied but not guaranteed.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Most secure internet communication relies on centralized authority-based trust relationships, such as those used in HTTPS, where public certificate authorities (CAs) vouch for the authenticity of websites.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] This same centralized trust model underpins protocols like OIDC (OpenID Connect) where identity providers (e.g., Google) authenticate users on behalf of relying applications.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In contrast, decentralized peer-based trust, also known as a web of trust, is commonly used for personal services such as secure email or file sharing.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In systems like PGP, trust is established when individuals personally verify and sign each other’s cryptographic keys, without relying on a central authority.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] These systems use cryptographic protocols that, in theory, are not vulnerable to spoofing as long as the originator’s private key remains uncompromised.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Importantly, even if the key owner is unaware of a compromise, the cryptographic failure still invalidates trust.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] However, while these methods are currently considered secure, they are not provably unbreakable—future mathematical or computational advances (such as quantum computing or new algorithmic attacks) could expose vulnerabilities.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] If that happens, it could retroactively undermine trust in past communications or agreements.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] For example, a digitally signed contract might be challenged if the signature algorithm is later found to be insecure..
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The ways in which someone may be authenticated fall into three categories, based on what is known as the factors of authentication: something the user knows, something the user has, and something the user is.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Each authentication factor covers a range of elements used to authenticate or verify a person's identity before being granted access, approving a transaction request, signing a document or other work product, granting authority to others, and establishing a chain of authority.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Security research has determined that for a positive authentication, elements from at least two, and preferably all three, factors should be verified.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Ownership: Something the user has (e.g., wrist band, ID card, security token, implanted device, cell phone with a built-in hardware token, software token, or cell phone holding a software token).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Inherence: Something the user is or does (e.g., fingerprint, retinal pattern, DNA sequence (there are assorted definitions of what is sufficient), signature, face, voice, unique bio-electric signals, or other biometric identifiers).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Historically, fingerprints have been used as the most authoritative method of authentication, but court cases in the US and elsewhere have raised fundamental doubts about fingerprint reliability.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Outside of the legal system as well, fingerprints are easily spoofable, with British Telecom's top computer security official noting that "few" fingerprint readers have not already been tricked by one spoof or another.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Hybrid or two-tiered authentication methods offer a compelling solution, such as private keys encrypted by fingerprint inside of a USB device.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] As the weakest level of authentication, only a single component from one of the three categories of factors is used to authenticate an individual's identity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The use of only one factor does not offer much protection from misuse or malicious intrusion.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] This type of authentication is not recommended for financial or personally relevant transactions that warrant a higher level of security.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Multi-factor authentication involves two or more authentication factors (something you know, something you have, or something you are).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Two-factor authentication is a special case of multi-factor authentication involving exactly two factors.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] For example, using a bank card (something the user has) along with a PIN (something the user knows) provides two-factor authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Business networks may require users to provide a password (knowledge factor) and a pseudorandom number from a security token (ownership factor).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Access to a very-high-security system might require a mantrap screening of height, weight, facial, and fingerprint checks (several inherence factor elements) plus a PIN and a day code (knowledge factor elements), but this is still a two-factor authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The United States government's National Information Assurance Glossary defines strong authentication as a layered authentication approach relying on two or more authenticators to establish the identity of an originator or receiver of information.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The European Central Bank (ECB) has defined strong authentication as "a procedure based on two or more of the three authentication factors".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The factors that are used must be mutually independent and at least one factor must be "non-reusable and non-replicable", except in the case of an inherence factor and must also be incapable of being stolen off the Internet.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] In the European, as well as in the US-American understanding, strong authentication is very similar to multi-factor authentication or 2FA, but exceeding those with more rigorous requirements.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The FIDO Alliance has been striving to establish technical specifications for strong authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Conventional computer systems authenticate users only at the initial log-in session, which can be the cause of a critical security flaw.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] To resolve this problem, systems need continuous user authentication methods that continuously monitor and authenticate users based on some biometric trait(s).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] A study used behavioural biometrics based on writing styles as a continuous authentication method.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Recent research has shown the possibility of using smartphones sensors and accessories to extract some behavioral attributes such as touch dynamics, keystroke dynamics and gait recognition.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] These attributes are known as behavioral biometrics and could be used to verify or identify users implicitly and continuously on smartphones.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The authentication systems that have been built based on these behavioral biometric traits are known as active or continuous authentication systems.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The term digital authentication, also known as electronic authentication or e-authentication, refers to a group of processes where the confidence for user identities is established and presented via electronic methods to an information system.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] The digital authentication process creates technical challenges because of the need to authenticate individuals or entities remotely over a network.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Authentication – After becoming a subscriber, the user receives an authenticator e.g., a token and credentials, such as a user name.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] He or she is then permitted to perform online transactions within an authenticated session with a relying party, where they must provide proof that he or she possesses one or more authenticators.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Life-cycle maintenance – the CSP is charged with the task of maintaining the user's credential over the course of its lifetime, while the subscriber is responsible for maintaining his or her authenticator(s).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authentication] Extra identity factors can be required to authenticate each party's identity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] In the context of an HTTP transaction, **basic access authentication** is a method for an HTTP user agent (e.g. a web browser) to provide a user name and password when making a request.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] In basic HTTP authentication, a request contains a header field in the form of `Authorization: Basic <credentials>`, where `<credentials>` is the Base64 encoding of ID and password joined by a single colon `:`.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] It was originally implemented by Ari Luotonen at CERN in 1993 and defined in the HTTP 1.0 specification in 1996.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] It is specified in RFC 7617 from 2015, which obsoletes RFC 2617 from 1999.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] HTTP Basic authentication (BA) implementation is the simplest technique for enforcing access controls to web resources because it does not require cookies, session identifiers, or login pages; rather, HTTP Basic authentication uses standard fields in the HTTP header.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] The BA mechanism does not provide confidentiality protection for the transmitted credentials.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] They are merely encoded with Base64 in transit and not encrypted or hashed in any way.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] Therefore, basic authentication is typically used in conjunction with HTTPS to provide confidentiality.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] Because the BA field has to be sent in the header of each HTTP request, the web browser needs to cache credentials for a reasonable period of time to avoid constantly prompting the user for their username and password.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] Caching policy differs between browsers.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] HTTP does not provide a method for a web server to instruct the client to "log out" the user.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] However, there are a number of methods to clear cached credentials in certain web browsers.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] One of them is redirecting the user to a URL on the same domain, using credentials that are intentionally incorrect.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] However, this behavior is inconsistent between various browsers and browser versions.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] In modern browsers, cached credentials for basic authentication are typically cleared when clearing browsing history.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] Most browsers allow users to specifically clear only credentials, though the option may be hard to find, and typically clears credentials for all visited sites.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] Brute forcing credentials is not actively prevented or detected (unless a server-side mechanism is used).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] When the server wants the user agent to authenticate itself towards the server after receiving an unauthenticated request, it must send a response with a *HTTP 401 Unauthorized* status line and a *WWW-Authenticate* header field.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] This parameter indicates that the server expects the client to use UTF-8 for encoding username and password (see below).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] When the user agent wants to send authentication credentials to the server, it may use the *Authorization* header field.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] The resulting string is encoded into an octet sequence.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] The character set to use for this encoding is by default unspecified, as long as it is compatible with US-ASCII, but the server may suggest the use of UTF-8 by sending the *charset* parameter.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] The resulting string is encoded using a variant of Base64 (+/ and with padding).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] The authorization method and a space character (e.g.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] "Basic ") is then prepended to the encoded string.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/basic-access-authentication] For example, if the browser uses *Aladdin* as the username and *open sesame* as the password, then the field's value is the Base64 encoding of *Aladdin:open sesame*, or *QWxhZGRpbjpvcGVuIHNlc2FtZQ==*.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] For example, a server could generate a token that has the claim "logged in as administrator" and provide that to a client.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] The client could then use that token to prove that it is logged in as admin.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] The tokens can be signed by one party's private key (usually the server's) so that any party can subsequently verify whether the token is legitimate.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] If the other party, by some suitable and trustworthy means, is in possession of the corresponding public key, they too are able to verify the token's legitimacy.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] The tokens are designed to be compact, URL-safe, and usable, especially in a web-browser single-sign-on (SSO) context.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] JWT claims can typically be used to pass identity of authenticated users between an identity provider and a service provider, or any other type of claims as required by business processes.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] JWT relies on other JSON-based standards: JSON Web Signature and JSON Web Encryption.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Identifies which algorithm is used to generate the signature.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] indicates that this token is signed using HMAC-SHA256.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] JWA (JSON Web Algorithms) RFC 7518 introduces many more for both authentication and encryption.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Custom claims are usually also included, depending on the purpose of the token.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] and concatenating the two together with a period separator.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] That string is then run through the cryptographic algorithm specified in the header.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This example uses HMAC-SHA256 with a shared secret (public key algorithms are also defined).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] , but uses different non-alphanumeric characters and omits padding.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This resulting token can be easily passed into HTML and HTTP.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] In authentication, when a user successfully logs in, a JSON Web Token (JWT) is often returned.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This token should be sent to the client using a secure mechanism like an HTTP-only cookie.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Storing the JWT locally in browser storage mechanisms like local or session storage is discouraged.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This is because JavaScript running on the client-side (including browser extensions) can access these storage mechanisms, exposing the JWT and compromising security.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] By using this method, the JWT is never exposed to client-side JavaScript; this is the best approach to make use of your JWT while maintaining security best practices.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] When the client wants to access a protected route or resource, the user agent should send the JWT, typically in the `Authorization` HTTP header using the `Bearer` schema.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This is a stateless authentication mechanism as the user state is never saved in server memory.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] The server's protected routes will check for a valid JWT in the Authorization header, and if it is present, the user will be allowed to access protected resources.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] As JWTs are self-contained, all the necessary information is there, reducing the need to query the database multiple times.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] List of currently registered claim names can be obtained from IANA JSON Web Token Claims Registry.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] JSON web tokens may contain session state.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] But if project requirements allow session invalidation before JWT expiration, services can no longer trust token assertions by the token alone.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] To validate that the session stored in the token is not revoked, token assertions must be checked against a data store.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] This renders the tokens no longer stateless, undermining the primary advantage of JWTs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Security consultant Tim McLean reported vulnerabilities in some JWT libraries that used the `alg` field to incorrectly validate tokens, most commonly by accepting a `alg=none` token.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] While these vulnerabilities were patched, McLean suggested deprecating the `alg` field altogether to prevent similar implementation confusion.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Still, new `alg=none` vulnerabilities are still being found in the wild, with four CVEs filed in the 2018-2021 period having this cause.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Several JWT libraries were found to be vulnerable to an invalid Elliptic-curve attack in 2017.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/json-web-token] Some have argued that JSON web tokens are difficult to use securely due to the many different encryption algorithms and options available in the standard, and that alternate standards should be used instead for both web frontends and backends.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:oauth2-flows-deep/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
